  - key: ''
    value: Chi-won employs traditional Chinese literary allusions throughout—from the story of the arrogant critic who called others 'wine-jugs and rice-bags' to references about the perils of excess and the virtue of knowing when to withdraw from public service.
  - key: ''
    value: The petition uses extreme self-deprecation as a rhetorical strategy, following the conventions of Tang bureaucratic memorials, while simultaneously expressing the author's genuine discomfort with accepting charity.
  - key: ''
    value: Chi-won's repeated use of nature imagery (withered frames reviving, spring water sustaining) reflects both Buddhist and Daoist influences on Korean-Sino literary thought of the period.
